{
  "According to the ideal gas law, what happens to the pressure of a gas if its volume is halved at constant temperature?": "",
  "Pressure is halved": "",
  "Pressure doubles": "",
  "Pressure stays the same": "",
  "Pressure quadruples": "",
  "By Boyle's law (PV = constant at fixed T and n), halving V doubles P. This is an inverse relationship between pressure and volume.": "",
  "What is the value of the universal gas constant R in SI units?": "",
  "6.022 × 10²³ mol⁻¹": "",
  "8.314 J/(mol·K)": "",
  "0.0821 J/(mol·K)": "",
  "1.38 × 10⁻²³ J/K": "",
  "The universal gas constant R = 8.314 J/(mol·K). The value 1.38 × 10⁻²³ J/K is Boltzmann's constant, and 6.022 × 10²³ is Avogadro's number.": "",
  "A gas occupies 4 L at 300 K. If the gas is heated to 600 K at constant pressure, what is the new volume?": "",
  "4 L": "",
  "16 L": "",
  "2 L": "",
  "8 L": "",
  "By Charles's law (V/T = constant at fixed P and n), V₂ = V₁ × T₂/T₁ = 4 × 600/300 = 8 L. Volume is directly proportional to absolute temperature.": "",
  "The average translational kinetic energy of an ideal gas molecule depends on:": "",
  "Only the absolute temperature": "",
  "The volume of the container": "",
  "The pressure of the gas": "",
  "The type of gas molecule": "",
  "The average translational kinetic energy per molecule is KE = (3/2)k_BT, which depends only on absolute temperature T, not on the type of molecule, pressure, or volume.": "",
  "An ideal gas is compressed from 10 L to 5 L while the temperature changes from 300 K to 600 K. What happens to the pressure?": "",
  "It quadruples": "",
  "It stays the same": "",
  "It doubles": "",
  "It triples": "",
  "Using PV = nRT: P₂/P₁ = (T₂/T₁)(V₁/V₂) = (600/300)(10/5) = 2 × 2 = 4. The pressure quadruples.": "",
  "Which assumption is NOT part of the ideal gas model?": "",
  "Molecules move randomly in all directions": "",
  "Collisions between molecules are perfectly elastic": "",
  "Gas molecules have negligible volume compared to the container": "",
  "Molecules attract each other with significant intermolecular forces": "",
  "The ideal gas model assumes no intermolecular forces between molecules. Significant attractive or repulsive forces between molecules would make the gas non-ideal.": "",
  "How many moles of an ideal gas occupy 22.4 L at STP (0°C, 1 atm)?": "",
  "1 mol": "",
  "2 mol": "",
  "22.4 mol": "",
  "0.5 mol": "",
  "At STP (273.15 K, 1 atm), one mole of any ideal gas occupies 22.4 L. This is known as the molar volume at STP.": "",
  "According to kinetic molecular theory, temperature is a measure of:": "",
  "The total number of molecules": "",
  "The average speed of molecules only": "",
  "The total potential energy of molecules": "",
  "The average translational kinetic energy of the molecules": "",
  "Temperature is directly proportional to the average translational kinetic energy of gas molecules: KE_avg = (3/2)k_BT. Higher temperature means faster-moving molecules on average.": "",
  "If the absolute temperature of an ideal gas is tripled while volume is held constant, the pressure will:": "",
  "Increase ninefold": "",
  "Stay the same": "",
  "Triple": "",
  "Be reduced to one-third": "",
  "By Gay-Lussac's law (P/T = constant at fixed V and n), tripling T at constant V triples P. Pressure is directly proportional to absolute temperature at constant volume.": "",
  "Two containers of ideal gas at the same temperature contain different gases. Container A has helium (He) and container B has nitrogen (N₂). Which statement is true?": "",
  "Speed cannot be compared without knowing pressure": "",
  "Both have the same average molecular speed": "",
  "Nitrogen molecules move faster on average": "",
  "Helium molecules move faster on average": "",
  "At the same temperature, all gas molecules have the same average kinetic energy. Since KE = (1/2)mv², lighter helium molecules (4 g/mol) must move faster than heavier nitrogen molecules (28 g/mol).": "",
  "What is the 'ideal gas law'?": "",
  "PV = nRT, relating pressure, volume, amount, and temperature of a gas": "",
  "Q = mcΔT, relating heat to temperature change": "",
  "F = ma applied to gas molecules": "",
  "E = mc², relating energy to mass": "",
  "The ideal gas law PV = nRT relates pressure (P), volume (V), number of moles (n), the gas constant (R = 8.314 J/(mol·K)), and absolute temperature (T in kelvins).": "",
  "What does 'Boyle's law' state?": "",
  "Pressure is inversely proportional to volume at constant temperature": "",
  "Volume is inversely proportional to temperature at constant pressure": "",
  "Pressure is directly proportional to temperature at constant volume": "",
  "Volume is directly proportional to temperature at constant pressure": "",
  "Boyle's law states that for a fixed amount of gas at constant temperature, PV = constant. As volume decreases, pressure increases proportionally.": "",
  "What does 'Charles's law' describe?": "",
  "The relationship between amount of gas and pressure": "",
  "The relationship between pressure and temperature at constant volume": "",
  "The direct proportionality between volume and absolute temperature at constant pressure": "",
  "The relationship between pressure and volume at constant temperature": "",
  "Charles's law states that at constant pressure, the volume of an ideal gas is directly proportional to its absolute temperature: V/T = constant.": "",
  "What is 'Boltzmann's constant'?": "",
  "The speed of light in vacuum": "",
  "A constant relating the average kinetic energy of particles to temperature: k_B = 1.38 × 10⁻²³ J/K": "",
  "The number of molecules in one mole": "",
  "The proportionality constant in Coulomb's law": "",
  "Boltzmann's constant k_B = 1.38 × 10⁻²³ J/K bridges macroscopic and microscopic physics. It relates the average kinetic energy of a single molecule to temperature: KE = (3/2)k_BT.": "",
  "What is meant by 'root-mean-square (rms) speed' of gas molecules?": "",
  "The maximum speed any molecule can reach": "",
  "The most probable speed of gas molecules": "",
  "The square root of the average of the squared speeds of all molecules": "",
  "The average of the absolute values of molecular speeds": "",
  "The rms speed is v_rms = sqrt(3k_BT/m) = sqrt(3RT/M). It is a measure of the typical molecular speed and is slightly higher than both the average and most probable speeds.": "",
  "What does 'mean free path' refer to for a gas molecule?": "",
  "The total distance a molecule travels in one second": "",
  "The diameter of a gas molecule": "",
  "The average distance a molecule travels between collisions with other molecules": "",
  "The distance a molecule travels before hitting a wall": "",
  "The mean free path is the average distance a gas molecule travels between successive collisions with other molecules. It increases with lower pressure (fewer molecules per volume).": "",
  "What is an 'isothermal process'?": "",
  "A process at constant pressure": "",
  "A process at constant volume": "",
  "A process at constant temperature": "",
  "A process with no heat transfer": "",
  "An isothermal process occurs at constant temperature. For an ideal gas undergoing an isothermal process, PV = constant (Boyle's law).": "",
  "What does 'Avogadro's number' represent?": "",
  "The total mass of one mole of hydrogen": "",
  "The maximum number of gas molecules in a container": "",
  "The number of atoms in 1 gram of any element": "",
  "The number of particles (atoms or molecules) in one mole: approximately 6.022 × 10²³": "",
  "Avogadro's number N_A = 6.022 × 10²³ mol⁻¹ is the number of particles in one mole of any substance. It connects macroscopic measurements (moles) to microscopic quantities (individual molecules).": "",
  "What is 'Dalton's law of partial pressures'?": "",
  "The total pressure of a gas mixture equals the sum of the partial pressures of each component gas": "",
  "The total pressure of a gas mixture equals the product of the individual gas pressures": "",
  "Each gas in a mixture exerts the same pressure regardless of its amount": "",
  "Gases in a mixture always separate by density": "",
  "Dalton's law states P_total = P₁ + P₂ + P₃ + ... where each partial pressure is the pressure that gas would exert if it alone occupied the entire volume at the same temperature.": "",
  "What is an 'adiabatic process'?": "",
  "A process that occurs infinitely slowly": "",
  "A process in which no heat is exchanged with the surroundings": "",
  "An adiabatic process is one in which no heat (Q) is transferred between the system and its surroundings (Q = 0). Rapid compressions and expansions are approximately adiabatic.": "",
  "A car tire contains air at a gauge pressure of 220 kPa and a temperature of 20°C (293 K). After a long drive, the temperature rises to 50°C (323 K). Assuming the tire volume is constant, what is the new gauge pressure? (P_atm = 101 kPa)": "",
  "About 220 kPa": "",
  "About 253 kPa": "",
  "About 243 kPa": "",
  "About 320 kPa": "",
  "Absolute initial pressure = 220 + 101 = 321 kPa. At constant V: P₂ = P₁(T₂/T₁) = 321 × (323/293) ≈ 354 kPa. New gauge pressure = 354 − 101 ≈ 253 kPa.": "",
  "A weather balloon is filled with helium to a volume of 1.0 m³ at sea level (P = 101 kPa, T = 300 K). As it rises, the external pressure drops to 30 kPa and the temperature falls to 220 K. What is the balloon's approximate volume at altitude?": "",
  "About 2.5 m³": "",
  "About 5.0 m³": "",
  "About 0.5 m³": "",
  "About 1.0 m³": "",
  "Using the combined gas law: V₂ = V₁ × (P₁/P₂) × (T₂/T₁) = 1.0 × (101/30) × (220/300) = 1.0 × 3.37 × 0.733 ≈ 2.47 m³ ≈ 2.5 m³.": "",
  "A scuba diver's tank holds 12 L of air at 200 atm and 20°C. If the diver breathes the air at 4 atm (underwater pressure at depth), what total volume of air is available at that depth, assuming constant temperature?": "",
  "300 L": "",
  "48 L": "",
  "600 L": "",
  "2400 L": "",
  "By Boyle's law: V₂ = V₁ × P₁/P₂ = 12 × 200/4 = 600 L. This is the total volume of air available at the underwater pressure of 4 atm.": "",
  "A sealed, rigid container holds 2 moles of an ideal gas at 400 K and 3 atm. If 3 additional moles of the same gas are pumped in at the same temperature, what is the new pressure?": "",
  "5 atm": "",
  "9 atm": "",
  "6 atm": "",
  "7.5 atm": "",
  "At constant T and V, P is proportional to n. New total moles = 2 + 3 = 5. P₂ = P₁ × (n₂/n₁) = 3 × (5/2) = 7.5 atm.": "",
  "In a laboratory, nitrogen gas (N₂, M = 28 g/mol) is at 300 K. What is the approximate rms speed of nitrogen molecules? (R = 8.314 J/(mol·K))": "",
  "About 340 m/s": "",
  "About 517 m/s": "",
  "About 1000 m/s": "",
  "About 250 m/s": "",
  "v_rms = sqrt(3RT/M) = sqrt(3 × 8.314 × 300 / 0.028) = sqrt(267,879) ≈ 517 m/s.": "",
  "A hot air balloon works by heating the air inside the envelope to 100°C (373 K) while the outside air is at 20°C (293 K). If the balloon has a volume of 2800 m³ at the higher temperature, what is the mass of air displaced by the balloon compared to the mass of hot air inside? (Air density at 20°C ≈ 1.2 kg/m³)": "",
  "The hot air is about 50% lighter": "",
  "There is no density difference": "",
  "The hot air is about 21% lighter, providing lift": "",
  "The hot air is about 5% lighter": "",
  "At constant pressure, density is inversely proportional to temperature: ρ_hot/ρ_cold = T_cold/T_hot = 293/373 ≈ 0.785. The hot air is about 21.5% less dense, providing buoyant lift.": "",
  "A chemist mixes 2 atm of oxygen and 3 atm of nitrogen in a rigid, sealed container at the same temperature. According to Dalton's law, what is the total pressure in the container?": "",
  "3 atm": "",
  "2.5 atm": "",
  "By Dalton's law, P_total = P_O₂ + P_N₂ = 2 + 3 = 5 atm. Each gas contributes its partial pressure independently.": "",
  "An engineer designs a pressurized cabin for an aircraft. The cabin holds 50 m³ of air at 1 atm and 20°C. How many moles of air are in the cabin? (R = 0.0821 L·atm/(mol·K))": "",
  "About 208 mol": "",
  "About 20,800 mol": "",
  "About 50 mol": "",
  "About 2,080 mol": "",
  "n = PV/(RT) = (1 atm × 50,000 L)/(0.0821 × 293) = 50,000/24.05 ≈ 2,079 mol ≈ 2,080 mol.": "",
  "A cylinder of gas is stored in a warehouse where summer temperatures reach 45°C (318 K) and winter temperatures drop to -5°C (268 K). If the gas pressure is 10 atm at 45°C, what will the pressure be in winter? (Assume constant volume.)": "",
  "About 12 atm": "",
  "About 6 atm": "",
  "About 8.4 atm": "",
  "About 10 atm": "",
  "At constant volume: P₂ = P₁ × T₂/T₁ = 10 × 268/318 ≈ 8.43 atm ≈ 8.4 atm.": "",
  "A syringe with no leaks contains 60 mL of gas at atmospheric pressure (100 kPa). A nurse pushes the plunger, reducing the volume to 20 mL at constant temperature. What is the gas pressure inside the syringe?": "",
  "150 kPa": "",
  "200 kPa": "",
  "33.3 kPa": "",
  "300 kPa": "",
  "By Boyle's law: P₂ = P₁ × V₁/V₂ = 100 × 60/20 = 300 kPa. Compressing the gas to one-third its volume triples the pressure.": ""
}